  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Some key legal requirements include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n2. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance\n- Establish internal control systems\n- Report suspicious activities\n- Maintain transaction records\n\n3. Reporting requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report cash transactions over certain thresholds\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\n4. Risk assessment\n- Identify potential money laundering risks\n- Implement risk mitigation strategies\n- Conduct regular audits\n\n5. Employee training\n- Educate staff about money laundering indicators\n- Train personnel to recognize suspicious activities\n- Maintain compliance awareness\n\n6. Legal penalties\n- Potential significant fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically governed by laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nFailure to comply can result in substantial financial and legal consequences for financial institutions.",
